




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Technological Opportunities and New Firm Creation
AU  - Shane, Scott
Y1  - 2001/02/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.47.2.205.9837
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.47.2.205.9837
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 205
EP  - 220
VL  - 47
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Research on the creation of new high-technology companies has typically focused either on industry-level factors such as market structure and technology regime or on individual-level factors such as the work experience of entrepreneurs. This study complements these approaches by examining the effect of technological opportunities on firm formation. In particular, the study shows that the probability that an invention will be commercialized through firm formation is influenced by its importance, radicalness, and patent scope.
AB  - Research on the creation of new high-technology companies has typically focused either on industry-level factors such as market structure and technology regime or on individual-level factors such as the work experience of entrepreneurs. This study complements these approaches by examining the effect of technological opportunities on firm formation. In particular, the study shows that the probability that an invention will be commercialized through firm formation is influenced by its importance, radicalness, and patent scope.
